Bash can sort numbers pretty efficiently
========================================

I usually hang out in `#bash` on Freenode IRC.  Bash is a really nice shell and
the people in that channel are always friendly.  Well, most of them are.

Playing around with arrays, I found this trick:

```bash
sortuniq () {
  for number
  do
    dumb[$number]=0
  done
  echo ${!dumb[@]}
}
```

It works like this:

`$ sortuniq 1 3 1 6 2
1 2 3 6`

The output is the same as `sort | uniq` (or `sort -u`), hence the name.

This is a pseudo-sorting algorithm that runs in **O(n)** :)  
It's basically a bucket sort, it works for integers from 0 to 2**63 -1.

It works like a charm for numbers.  Then why not declaring `dumb` as an
associative array and use it for strings too?  Well, strings are a completely
different matter.  Associative arrays are hashed, the hashing function is like

`i=0; for char in string; do ((i*=16777619, i^=ord(char) )); done`

which _happens_ to "work" when the string is only 1-char long.

That sorting function can be minified to this:

`s()(for n;do d[$n]=;done;echo ${!d[@]})`

Only 39 bytes. It's pretty cool, imho.

Apparently nobody knew about this, so... yeah...

